Analysing and Visualising the Dataset of UFA Film¶

In this notebook I would like to analyse a dataset that comes from the Super8database.org (an amateur platform collecting Super8 reductions prints from international sources). This dataset contains a list of films that were distributed by UFA-Buscher Film in Germany in the seventies and early eighties. This company specialised in the distribution of "reduction prints" (reduced versions of films to be watched at home) on Super8-mm film material and had a specific library of film genres. In my analysis I want to give a glimpse in form of a "distant reading" of the film library, the most represented genres, directors, country of origins and original language of the distributions, in order to understand what was popular among reduction prints buyers.

The Dataset has been enriched with additional data through the software Open Refine. To the original Ufa Title of the films, the number of reels, color or b/w type I added and reconciled the original title (the Ufa title was usually different than the original copy because reduction prints were often edited and shortened versions). From the original title I could add other fields as columns: director, original language, genre (limited to only 1 item), IMDb ID, year of production and country of origin.

To proceed to further analyse and later visualize my dataset I download the packages for python:

Looking at other people work on film lists I also want to show only the most frequent genres and group those that are coming less often into a single group in order to visualize it better in a chart. I took part of the code from github page of CamPaiva.

In [9]:
#counting the frequency of genres per film 

genre_list = pd.DataFrame(ufa_df.genre.value_counts())
genre_list["Frequency"] = ufa_df.genre.value_counts(normalize=True)
genre_list = genre_list.reset_index()
genre_list = genre_list.rename(columns = {"index": "genre", "count": "Number of Films"})
genre_list.loc[genre_list.Frequency < 0.03, 'genre'] = 'Others'
genre_list = (genre_list
                .groupby('genre').sum()
                .sort_values('Number of Films', ascending=False)
                .reset_index())
print(genre_list)

A pie chart might represent the percentages within the whole dataset better. Let's see. I added a legend on the bottom right corner. We might see that the most represented genres are comedy, action and horror film. Even science fiction has a higher percentage than drama. This shows how this dataset of films might differ from the most popular films in theaters. These films were only distributed for the home entertainment.

Analysing Country of Origin and Original language¶

We might now do the same operation of analysis to look at the most represented countries of origin and original language in the dataset, and later also count the most represented directors.

Now I create a list based on the original language:¶

In [21]:
language_list = pd.DataFrame(ufa_df.original_language.value_counts())
language_list["Frequency"] = ufa_df.original_language.value_counts(normalize=True)
language_list = language_list.reset_index()
language_list = language_list.rename(columns = {"index": "original_language", "count": "Number of Films"})
language_list.loc[language_list.Frequency < 0.013605, 'original_language'] = 'Others'
language_list = (language_list
                .groupby('original_language').sum()
                .sort_values('Number of Films', ascending=False)
                .reset_index())

print(language_list)
